## Problem

Tests that use Swift Testing (`@Test` / `@Suite` / `#expect`) and instantiate a real `Application` via `Application.make(.testing)` + `app.startup()` fail at startup because `Environment.testing.sanitizeArguments()` doesn't recognise Swift Testing's test runner.

Concretely, in [Sources/Vapor/Environment/Environment.swift](https://github.com/vapor/vapor/blob/main/Sources/Vapor/Environment/Environment.swift):

```swift
private static func sanitize(commandInput: inout CommandInput) {
    #if Xcode
    // strip -NS / -Apple ...
    #elseif os(macOS) || os(iOS) || os(tvOS) || os(watchOS)
    if commandInput.executable.hasSuffix("/usr/bin/xctest") {
        if commandInput.arguments.first?.lowercased() == "-xctest" && commandInput.arguments.count > 1 {
            commandInput.arguments.removeFirst(2)
        }
        if commandInput.arguments.first?.hasSuffix(".xctest") ?? false {
            commandInput.arguments.removeFirst()
        }
    }
    #endif
    // ...
}
```

The `hasSuffix("/usr/bin/xctest")` branch handles XCTest. Swift Testing under SwiftPM is invoked through `swiftpm-testing-helper`, whose argv includes `--test-bundle-path`, `--filter`, `--testing-library swift-testing`. None of these are stripped.

## Symptom

When the test calls `try await app.startup()`, the merged async command group is invoked via `console.run`, which receives `--test-bundle-path` as the first arg. `AsyncCommandGroup.run` treats it as a command name and throws `CommandError.unknownCommand`:

```
DBG: before startup
DBG: startup THREW: Unknown command `--test-bundle-path`
```

If the test does not wrap startup in `do/catch`, the throw skips `try await app.asyncShutdown()`. `Application.deinit` then runs the sync fallback `self.shutdown()`. The sync `storage.shutdown()` only invokes `onShutdown` closures, not `onAsyncShutdown`. `ServeCommand` is registered with an async-only handler (via `Application.make` → `asyncCommand` → `storage.setWithAsyncShutdown`), so its cleanup is silently skipped. `ServeCommand.deinit` then trips:

```
Vapor/ServeCommand.swift:131: Assertion failed: ServeCommand did not shutdown before deinit
```

The process aborts with SIGTRAP.

## Reproduction

Minimal Swift Testing repro on Vapor 4.121.4 / Swift 6.1:

```swift
import Testing
import Vapor

@Suite struct ReproTests {
  @Test func minimalStartup() async throws {
    let app = try await Application.make(.testing)
    try await configure(app)
    app.http.server.configuration.port = 0
    try await app.startup()         // throws: Unknown command `--test-bundle-path`
    try await app.asyncShutdown()
  }
}
```

The same test under XCTest (`final class : XCTestCase`, `func testMinimalStartup()`) passes silently, because `sanitize` strips xctest's args.

## Workaround

Construct a testing environment with clean args directly, bypassing `sanitizeArguments()`:

```swift
let env = Environment(name: "testing", arguments: ["vapor"])
let app = try await Application.make(env)
```

With a single-element `arguments` array, `console.run` falls through to the default `serve` command and `app.startup()` returns normally.

## Suggested fix

Extend the sanitize match to recognise the Swift Testing runner. The runner executable for SwiftPM-based Swift Testing is `swiftpm-testing-helper`, and its args take the shape `--test-bundle-path <path> [--filter <name>] [...] <path> --testing-library swift-testing`. A targeted strip in the existing `sanitize`:

```swift
} else if commandInput.executable.hasSuffix("/swiftpm-testing-helper") {
    // Strip everything; Swift Testing doesn't pass anything Vapor cares about.
    commandInput.arguments = []
}
```

This mirrors the spirit of the XCTest branch and avoids the need for every Swift Testing user to construct a custom `Environment`.

## Environment

- Vapor 4.121.4
- Swift 6.1 (Xcode 16.4 / macos-15)
- Swift Testing 1902 (the version shipped with Swift 6.1)
- Reproducible on macOS 26.3 locally and macos-15 GitHub Actions runners.

Happy to send a PR if the suggested fix shape is acceptable.

### Please summarize your feature request

ClientResponse cannot quickly throw a non-200 error.

### Describe the functionality you're seeking in more detail

When I use a `client` to retrieve data, I always need to handle `response.status` separately.

like this:
```swift
let response = try await app.client.get(uri)

// There is always a need to handle repetitive tasks.
switch response.status {
case .ok:
    return try response.content.decode(String.self, as: .plainText)
default:
    throw Abort(response.status)
```

Then I thought of validateStatus, which is commonly used in iOS development.
```swift
// This is just a demo; there may be better implementations.
extension ClientResponse {
    func validateStatus(_ status: [HTTPStatus] = [.ok]) throws -> ClientResponse {
        guard status.contains(self.status) else {
            throw Abort(self.status, reason: self.status.reasonPhrase)
        }
        return self
    }
}

try await client.get(uri, headers: innerHeaders)
    .validateStatus() // <-- here to throw status error
    .content
    .decode([Model].self, using: JSONDecoder())
```

